    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Ottawa started as Bytown in 1826, named for engineer John By, and was renamed Ottawa in 1855 when it gained city status.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        7,
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottawa"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Ottawa was chosen as the capital of the Province of Canada in 1857 and kept that title when Canada became a dominion in 1867.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3,
        10,
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.britannica.com/place/Ottawa"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Rideau Canal, never used militarily, was key to Ottawa’s early growth by moving timber, goods, and people during the 19th‑century boom.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        24
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.britannica.com/place/Ottawa"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The University of Ottawa, originally the College of Bytown, opened its doors in 1848 as the city’s first post‑secondary school.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
